reservations.comment:
Michael's response to the assignment:


"

I have seen this video before as I frequent this style of debrief on AOPA and various other channels (Did watch again, of course!). I will outline a couple of key points below and how they relate to my recent omission of procedure during the prog check.


- This particular pilot had quite a bit of experience and ratings, and it appears that complacency got him away from SOP. Thoughts like, “I’ll take care of that later” or “I’ve done this before so we should be okay” can be a catastrophic mindset. Shortly after takeoff and above 1,000 AGL, I completed my climb checklist. Following completion of the climb checklist, I commented that I didn’t want to perform the cruise checklist because I would soon be climbing as the Bravo shelf lifted. I thought to myself, “I’ve done this so many times before, there’s no way I’d forget today”. As I was waiting to ensure I was clear of the bravo, I switched over from my checklists and began to focus on Pilotage, dead-reckoning, my charts and my logs to ensure I knew my precise location. I had made up my mind that I would climb later, but never really made a deliberate decision as to when I would begin my climb. This lead to me not only leaving the mixture full rich due to low altitude and pre-climb to cruising altitude, but it also left me in denser air where my airspeed and power settings were naturally different than planned. As Evan increased my workload with some basic questions, my mind drifted further and further from climbing and leaning for projected speeds and fuel burn, and I flew further and further beyond where I could have initiated my climb. As task saturation increased, my mind drifted further and further away from SOP.


- The video also highlighted that the airplane may have made it safely had the flight been VFR direct into the airport, but this is not what ended up happening. As pilots we must always plan for the unexpected whether it be delays in the air, diversions due to weather or problems with the airplane. Conserve fuel as if you are expected delays getting back on the ground rather than using more because plenty is onboard at the time. Allowing myself to get comfortable with the fuel level onboard and not place enough emphasis on following my flight plan and the SOP more closely could lead to catastrophe once unforeseen hazards or delays occur. Given what happened during the program check, my XC flight plan would have me assuming I have more than enough fuel, but from the very beginning I was using more fuel than I had planned.


- The final opportunity this pilot had to save the lives aboard was, once again, to follow SOPs and, what I assume to be, emergency memory items for dual and/or single engine failure in the Baron. The fact that he restarted one engine indicates that he at least performed some memory items properly, but as stress level and workload increased, a few critical errors were made. Propeller was not feathered on the inop engine and flaps were not raised leading to a known inability for the Baron to accelerate or hold altitude. The final fatal mistake was most likely item #1 on the engine failure memory items. “Pitch for best glide of ___kts”. This again highlights that a pilot with far more experience than I have can be quickly saturated beyond recovery. As they say, “giving the Swiss cheese model more opportunity to line up more holes”.


Regularly check myself for complacency and continue to expand aviation knowledge and practical skills. Stick to the SOPs 100%, stick to the checklists 100%, and practice even when I feel proficiency is at or above par."

reservations.comment:
GPS NAVIGATION

- T routes do not need WAAS, just GPS (“RNAV Route GNSS required”)

- GNSS is umbrella term for GPS type navigation; SBAS is umbrella term for WAAS type navigation (GPS + WAAS are USA specific systems)

- review GPS theory of operation:

- - GPS satellites only send, do not receive information from user element; see coarse/acquisition code

- - WAAS satellites are geosynchronous, GPS satellites are not

- - pseudoranging good, trilateration needs 4 satellites to get 3D position

- RAIM explanation good!

reservations.comment:
• Basic instrument flight maneuvers - This is marginally satisfactory and will need more work to move to ACS as well as professional level for Part 121/135 standards. Heading changes are often excessive. Use your heading bug to command intentional headings. Use the bug as a cage (its has a lateral deviation of 5 degrees left and right of the selection. You can deviate you heading the lateral limits of the bug, but any more requires a bug change before a greater heading change.) This will avoid unintentional heading deviations and excessive corrections. Climb at Vy until critical altitude which is 1,000’ AGL (then transition to a cruise climb). 
  • Intercepting and tracking navigation systems - Initial intercept heading assignment was 300 not 320, this led to an overshoot on heading. The second intercept heading was also an overshoot. Use your heading bug to help avoid these overshoots.
  • Intercepting and tracking DME arcs - Large heading changes led to deviation as much as 0.5 miles from the arc. This can be reduced by making smaller intentional heading changes with the heading bug. 
  • Holding - Drew the hold incorrectly with left turns, but may have been disoriented based on the holding location and which leg was drawn as the inbound and the outbound leg. Selected a parallel entry when the correct entry is a direct. This positioned the aircraft northwest of the fix rather than southeast. Did not report reaching the holding fix. The second hold entry was properly selected but OBS wasn’t selected prior to crossing the fix so the flight sequenced on to the following fix (VANNI). In this case the Course tracking was off.

reservations.comment:
Takeoffs and landings ground trainer number 2.


We are not taking the winds into consideration, which is the reason we are overshooting the runway all the time. You need to think about what the winds are doing, where are they coming from, and how is that going to affect and change your traffic pattern operation.


There were also a lot of times when we were either high, low, fast, or slow. You need to start asking yourself that question, am I high, low, fast, slow? And go ahead with the proper corrective action.


Talking yourself thru the landings may be a useful thing to do, but remember in the actual plane we also have radios to take care off and other factors that might get in the way, but we cannot allow that to stop us from continuing our configuration.

When it comes to checklist, please make sure you follow them, you’re skipping over certain items and we don’t want to do that.


We are over controlling the rudders and not compensating enough for our crosswinds.


We were coming in high in all the landings but not once we tried to apply a forward slip, instead you we pushing in the elevator forward and aft, forward and aft, forward and aft, which is not the proper way to lose altitude.

reservations.comment:
-Study the SOP.

-Study flows and checklist.

-You have to be able to apply the information from the SOP without looking at the SOP during flight. I don’t expect you to be perfect, but you should be able to at least tell me the procedure. I recommend study the SOP, write each maneuver out from memory, and then chair each maneuver until you can do the maneuver from memory.

-Always remember to write down taxi instructions, brief it with airport diagram, brief hotspot, complex intersections and runway crossing.

-Please read Chapter 4, sections 2 & 3 of the AIM.

-Listen to ATC live or YouTube to help with comms.

-Flight training is not easy, it requires a lot of studying and dedication.
reservations.name: Custom lesson

reservations.comment:
-Remember to sump the fuel.

-If the oil is too hot from the last flight, it might be hard to see where the oil is at because of the viscosity of the oil, so I recommend using a clean towel to check the oil.

-Review the leaning procedure for when we are on the ground and in flight.

-Ensure that you put the chock under the rear seat of the airplane.

-Try and study the airport diagram and find ways how to navigate to the practice areas.

-Ensure that you are calling each checklist before and after completion.

-When we are climbing, we should add full power while simultaneously increasing our pitch to climb at Vy or cruise climb so we don't overspeed the prop.

-Remember we use the rudder to initiate the turn, once the turn is established, we hold that rudder pressure to stay coordinated and release when we finish the turn.

-Remember the left turning tendencies and how to counter them when turning left or right. During a left turn, we use rudder to start the turn, but it requires less rudder because of the left turning tendencies. Conversely, the opposite will happen in a right turn. So, more right rudder is needed in a right turn.

-The left turning tendencies will be more significant when we are full power and at a higher AOA.

-Continue to study the flows and checklist. As you can see today, when the airport is busy, we don't have time to waste on the ground because we were holding up traffic, and we always want to create a good working relationship with the controlling agency.

-Complete the phase 1 quiz

-Complete the ground lessons on the Cessna Training website.

Custom lesson - Progress Check Notes Review

reservations.comment:
• Overall throughout the flight: much better altitude and heading control. Pretty much maintained these to standards and corrected when needed. 
  • Better awareness of the Class B shelves on departure and approach. 
  • Good situational awareness with pattern entry. Was deliberate about entering at the 45 degree midfield right downwind 25 while scanning for traffic. 
  • Radio comms were solid overall. 


Preflight and Departure:

  • Fuel selector valve was on left tank during start (caught it without me saying anything)
  • Door was open during engine start (caught it without me saying anything)
  • Apopka is NW of KORL, not SE. Was confused about requesting a departure direction and thought it meant the runway direction (i.e. Taking off runway 25 would mean a southwest departure in all cases). 
  • Almost taxied to runway 7 via B, A, before I intervened. The runway assignment was 25. Copied taxi instructions on scratchpad, but did not have taxi diagram out and did not have MFD zoomed for SafeTaxi. 
  • Didn’t have tower frequency ready prior to lineup. Almost requested takeoff clearance on ground before I pointed it out. 
  • Landing light was off for takeoff.
  • Assigned “runway heading” on departure but wasn’t aware. Tower should have repeated instruction, to be fair.
  • Nav light was on during flight. Not needed during daytime. 
  • Cruise climb is full power. Wasn’t sure. 


Simulated engine failure:

  • Use NRST function. We were over X61 and FA83 airports. Found X61 visually though.
  • If over the field and high, start circling over the field. Don’t keep flying away.
  • Actually do the troubleshoot steps (except engaging starter). Left the mixture leaned for cruise on both attempts, and started to go around with leaned mixture.
  • First attempt: We were high. Forgot flaps were an option until prompted. 
  • Second attempt: still didn’t use full flaps when we were too high. 
  • Both attempts would have successfully made it stabilized into X61 had full flaps been used. 


Arrival:

  • Remember Descent and Before Landing checklists. Most of the items were done, but should be verified with checklist. 
  • Got slow on landing, recognized this and overcorrected with power. Bounced landing. Due to busy airspace, we had to full stop with no time for more landing practice. 
  • “Taxi back via A, B”. Almost turned onto east ramp at A5 instead of B before I intervened. 
  • Remember to turn off lights except beacon during shut down.
  • Tie down wings first, pull/push the plane back to tighten the wing tiedowns, then tie the tail. Don’t chock until after the plane is pulled back.
